<paragraph blockId="78.[151,1437,306,1493]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,447,1350,1376]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Taxonomic notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Henderson, Borchsenius &amp; Balslev" authorityYear="2008" box="[447,696,1350,1376]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Geonoma" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hollinensis">
<emphasis box="[447,696,1350,1376]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Geonoma hollinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of only two species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Willdenow" authorityYear="1805" box="[1047,1161,1350,1376]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Geonoma" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1047,1161,1350,1376]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Geonoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with staminate flowers with three stamens; 
<taxonomicName authority="Burret" authorityName="Burret" box="[402,539,1389,1415]" class="Liliopsida" family="Arecaceae" genus="Kalbreyera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Arecales" pageId="78" pageNumber="79" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="triandra">
<emphasis box="[402,539,1389,1415]" italics="true" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">G. triandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the other. Lacking staminate flowers, it can also be recognized by its vestigial peduncular bracts and tricussately arranged flower pits.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="78.[151,1437,306,1493]" box="[198,1308,1467,1493]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,500,1467,1493]" pageId="78" pageNumber="79">Subspecific variation:—</emphasis>
There is no variation in any trait amongst the four specimens known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
